x4freetext: The 13-MV HI-13 Tandem Accelerator
Tritium gas target contains tritium gas chamber
and helium gas chamber. Detailed informations:
The body of the tritium cell was a stainless-steel
cylinder that was 3.0 cm long and 1.1 cm in diameter
and had a wall with thickness of 0.2 mm. It was
filled with tritium gas to a pressure of 2.2 atm, 0.3
mm thick gold metal was used as a beam stop and as a
liner.
The helium gas cell was a tube with flanges at
both ends for mechanical connection and vacuum
sealing. It was 2.0 cm long and 1.1 cm in diameter
and was held at a pressure of about 0.3 atm.
A cylindrical Beryllium: height=40 mm; diameter=40
mm; 0 deg direction with respect to the deuteron
beam. The distance between the sample and the center
of the tritium gas target was about 20 cm.
A cylindrical Polyethylene: height=40 mm; diameter=30
mm, for monitor by n-p scattering.
Three fast neutron TOF spectrometers, employed
with 10 deg intervals to measure the secondary
neutrons. Each spectrometer consists of a BC-501A
liquid scintillator with diameter of 17.78 cm and
thickness of 10.16 cm, a XP2041 photomultiplier tube
and the collimator with effective shielding. The
flight length of the scattered neutrons between the
sample center and the detector center was 602, 687
and 512 cm, respectively.
A stilbene crystal detector was placed at 46.75 deg
direction with respect to the deuteron beam to measure
the intensity and spectrum of source neutrons in TOF
mode, which can be used for neutron fluence
normalization for the measurements. The flight length
of the source neutrons between tritium gas target
center and the monitor center was 754 cm.
The measured raw TOF spectra include
gas-in (sample-in/sample-out) and gas-out (sample-in/
sample-out). The net TOF spectra are determined by
subtracting the three runs background spectra (gas
in-sample out, gas out-sample in, gas out-sample out)
from the gas in-sample in spectra, and including the
propagation of uncertainties. All events from the
four detectors (three main detectors and one monitor)
were recorded in the list mode during the experiments.
For each event, there are three parameters, the pulse
height (PH), the pulse shape discrimination (PSD) and
the TOF. The PH and PSD were used for the detection
threshold determination and n-gamma discrimination.

x4freetext: ENDF/B-VII.1
Approved by Xichao Ruan.
Corrected for multiple scattering, fluence
attenuation in the sample and the finite geometry
effects by simulating TOF spectra by a Monte Carlo
code STREUER.
The total uncertainty of data include
statistical errors and systematic errors
The statistical uncertainties of
the measurement ranged from 0.4% at 20 deg to 19% at
145 deg
The systematic errors were mainly determined by
The neutron detection efficiency (5%)
The correction for multiple scattering (1%)
The scattering angle (0.5 degree)
the normalized scattering cross section
of n-p (1%)
Data presented by first author and
approved by Xichao Ruan
Qian Jing (CNDC)
